content:
You can tell a song’s mood in about two seconds of listening. A minor key with a slow tempo feels heavy. A major key with a driving beat feels euphoric. Your ears do this instantly — but if you’re building software, “instantly” isn’t good enough. You need that judgment expressed as data, at scale, on demand.
That’s the problem mood detection APIs solve. And if you’re building a music app, a video editor, a fitness app, or anything that needs to react to the emotional tone of a song, this is the layer you’re missing.
Why “Mood” Is Actually a Data Problem
Mood isn’t a single number. It’s a blend of several measurable signals working together:

• Key & Mode — major keys tend to read as bright or happy; minor keys read as somber or tense

• Tempo (BPM) — slow tracks feel relaxed or sad; fast tracks feel energetic or anxious

• Energy — how intense and active a track feels

• Danceability — how rhythmically consistent and “groove-able” a track is

• Happiness (Valence) — a direct measure of musical positivity

• Acousticness — organic, unplugged instrumentation vs. produced/electronic

• Loudness — overall perceived volume, which correlates with intensity
No single one of these tells the full story. A slow acoustic ballad in a major key can still feel bittersweet. A fast track in a minor key can feel aggressive rather than sad. The real signal comes from combining them — which is exactly why you want an API returning all of these at once, rather than trying to guess from metadata alone.
Meet the Track Analysis API
The Track Analysis API by SoundNet does the heavy lifting here. Instead of running your own audio-processing pipeline, you send a track name (or a Spotify Track ID) and get back a full musical fingerprint:
{
"id": "a396e5ef3e08c870041b67c0d0e7863d",
"name": "Respect",
"album": "I Never Loved a Man the Way I Love You",
"key": "C",
"mode": "major",
"camelot": "8B",
"tempo": 115,
"duration": "2:27",
"popularity": 77,
"energy": 56,
"danceability": 81,
"happiness": 97,
"acousticness": 16,
"instrumentalness": 0,
"liveness": 5,
"speechiness": 4,
"loudness": "-5 dB"
}That single response contains almost everything you need to classify mood — key, mode, tempo, energy, danceability, happiness, and acousticness — without you having to touch a waveform or train a model.
Three Ways to Query It
The API is deliberately flexible depending on what you already have on hand:
1. You have a Spotify Track ID — fastest, most accurate:
const spotifyTrackID = "7s25THrKz86DM225dOYwnr";
const url = `https://track-analysis.p.rapidapi.com/pktx/spotify/${spotifyTrackID}`;
const options = {
method: 'GET',
headers: {
'x-rapidapi-key': 'YOUR_RAPIDAPI_KEY',
'x-rapidapi-host': 'track-analysis.p.rapidapi.com'
}
};
const response = await fetch(url, options);
const result = await response.json();2. You only have song + artist name — no external dependency required:
const baseUrl = 'https://track-analysis.p.rapidapi.com/pktx/analysis';
const params = new URLSearchParams({
song: 'Respect',
artist: 'Aretha Franklin' // optional, but recommended for accuracy
});
const url = `${baseUrl}?${params.toString()}`;
const response = await fetch(url, options);
const result = await response.json();3. You just need key and tempo, fast — a lightweight endpoint for when you don’t need the full feature set:
// GET https://track-analysis.p.rapidapi.com/pktx/key-bpm?song=Respect&artist=Aretha%20Franklin
// Returns: { "id": "...", "key": "C", "mode": "major", "tempo": 115 }Building a Simple Mood Classifier
Here’s where it gets fun. With the full feature set from /pktx/analysis, you can write a lightweight scoring function that converts raw numbers into a human-readable mood label — no machine learning required to get started.
function classifyMood(track) {
const { mode, tempo, energy, happiness, acousticness, danceability } = track;
// Normalize a rough "positivity" score
const positivity = (happiness * 0.5) + (danceability * 0.25) + (mode === 'major' ? 25 : 0);
// Normalize a rough "intensity" score
const intensity = (energy * 0.6) + (tempo > 120 ? 20 : 0) + ((100 - acousticness) * 0.2);
if (positivity > 70 && intensity > 60) return 'Euphoric';
if (positivity > 70 && intensity <= 60) return 'Feel-Good / Chill';
if (positivity <= 40 && intensity > 60) return 'Aggressive / Tense';
if (positivity <= 40 && intensity <= 40) return 'Melancholic';
if (acousticness > 60 && positivity <= 50) return 'Bittersweet';
return 'Neutral / Mixed';
}
// Example usage
const track = await fetch(url, options).then(r => r.json());
console.log(classifyMood(track)); // "Feel-Good / Chill"This is intentionally simple — a starting point, not a final model. But it demonstrates the core idea: once the API gives you clean, structured features, mood classification becomes a function you write, not a research project you undertake.
Where This Actually Gets Used
Once you have reliable mood tags per track, a lot of product ideas become trivial to build:

• Smart playlist generation — auto-sort a user’s library into “hype,” “focus,” or “wind down” playlists based on real audio features instead of manual tagging

• Video editing tools — auto-suggest background tracks that match the energy of a clip

• Fitness apps — sync workout intensity phases (warm-up, peak, cooldown) to tempo and energy

• Audio-reactive visualizers — drive color, motion, or particle intensity off energy and danceability

• Recommendation engines — cluster a catalog by key/mode/tempo to find tracks that are harmonically and emotionally compatible (this is also where camelot notation becomes useful for DJ-style harmonic mixing)
Every one of these is a product feature that would otherwise require you to either license a much heavier audio-analysis stack or build your own signal-processing pipeline from scratch.
Getting Started
You don’t need your own Spotify API credentials or an audio-processing background to ship this. All you need is a RapidAPI key:
const options = {
method: 'GET',
headers: {
'x-rapidapi-key': 'YOUR_RAPIDAPI_KEY',
'x-rapidapi-host': 'track-analysis.p.rapidapi.com'
}
};Grab a key, hit /pktx/analysis with a song and artist, and you'll have a full feature payload back in one request. From there, the mood classifier above is maybe twenty lines of code between you and a working feature.
Music mood detection sounds like a hard problem — and building it from raw audio genuinely is. But once someone else has solved the signal-processing layer, all that’s left is deciding what story you want the numbers to tell.
Try the Track Analysis API on RapidAPI and see what your app sounds like when it can actually listen.
